item.title: Boardgame Insert for Sleeved Cards--Broken Token Style
item.description:
I wanted a horizontal organizer for sleeved Dominion cards, but couldn't find anything quite like what I wanted. I really love the Broken Token insert but since I have a 3d printer I wanted something I could print myself. I quickly mocked this up on Tinkercad and it worked great! It measures 288mm x 98mm x 65mm high. Should be easy to modify to fit any card heavy game. I plan to make another piece to hold things in place to make it easier to stack vertically, but until then it is working great.

This is a big file, and the only way I could get it to fit on my printer was to rotate it 45* and it just barely fit. One of the pictures shows this in Cura. Definitely print with a brim. The dividers were a VERY snug fit, and I like them that way so nothing moves around. I only printed 3, but print as many as you want.

This will fit two columns of sleeved cards, but won't quite fit three as you can see in one of the pictures. I took a picture before I sleeved the cards and the Dominion Base game plus the Prosperity expansion fit in one column. After sleeving it takes up one and a half.

item.title: Iron Man MK 85 Hinge Kit
item.description:
This is my complete parts kit for the MK85 Iron Man Helmet (.stl on Thingiverse). I designed this mostly for fun for myself at first but then had tremendous support from the 3D printing community after sharing my design. I designed this parts kit with the helmet printed at 100% scale, so take that into consideration, but it shouldn't impact anything with parts sizing.
You will need to shave some of the back of the face plate near the widow's peak in order for this system to work properly. I used a dremel and some patience and finally got the clearances I needed. I recommend using a dab of hot glue to place your parts and check alignment before making anything permanent. Once comfortable, I used a soldering iron to "plastic weld" the pieces in place.
Electronic Components I Used:
MG90S Servo(2)
Limit Switch (2)
2 Channel Relay board (1)
Plastic Reed Switch (2)
22 AWG Wire (more than I needed in some places, not enough in most)

item.description:
Settlers of Catan Player Case.

Full files on my Prusa Printers profile including the player cases for the player pieces.
https://www.prusaprinters.org/prints/124960-settlers-of-catan-6-player-case
https://www.prusaprinters.org/prints/124952-settlers-of-catan-player-piece-case

Case to fit the 6 player 3d printed version of Catan.
(Dakanzla files) https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2525047

4x 3d printed inserts to hold the terrain pieces for settlers of catan in the 6 players case I built. Each is sized 143mm x 182.5mm x 84.6mm
No supports needed in the printing of them.
In the bottoms of each piece I have a part just a couple layers thick showing the colour so that you know where to put the terrain pieces away.
I've printed them in 0.2mm layers.

All the pieces fit into a 390x312x182mm wooden box.
For the wood I used 12mm & 6mm MDF offcuts I had lying around.
You should be able to just get all the wooden pieces from 2 small sheets of MDF/plywood.
1x 900x600x12mm
1x 900x600x6mm
12mm MDF for the sides and top of the lid. 6mm for both horizontal parts and bottom of the lid. I then glued the box together with PVA and gave a clear coat of polyurethane.
I've uploaded the fusion 360 archive file so you can see how the case fits together and the sizes of the wood needed.

Designed to go with my base game player cases.
https://www.prusaprinters.org/prints/124952-settlers-of-catan-player-piece-case

Working on a 2nd case for the Cities & Knights & Seafarers expansions as well once I've finished printing my seafarers parts. (Cities & Knights already printed)

item.title: New Water Droplet Kinetic Desk Toy
item.description:
This is the newest updated version of my original Water Droplet Kinetic Sculpture.

-This version has thicker, better modeled rings that make it both easier to print and more stable when spinning.

-The updated crankshaft, inspired by supinemonkey's remix uses a smooth transition as opposed to the original stepped transition between rings. This updated shaft allows for a MUCH easier print which requires no supports by having both the smooth transition and by being split into multiple pieces.

-Along with the updated shaft comes an updated handle which is also inspired by supinemonkey here.

-The updated frame uses two 608 bearings for a much smoother rotation. The frame also holds the crank higher up so when turning, your hand doesn't keep hitting the desk.

Assembly is super easy. I tend to start with adding the crank to the body first so there's a little more room before the top and middle pieces go on. When attaching the crank to the bearings use 2 M3x10mm screws to attach the spacers and handle. Also on the handle side, be sure to attach the handle on the outside of the spacer so there is room for the handle to spin without binding. To attach the knob to the handle just use one more M3x10mm screw and tighten it just tight enough so the knob can still spin freely. Depending on your print settings you may experience stringing between the legs of the rings. If that happens, I've found that using a heat gun on the strings will tend to wick them away fairly easily.

item.title: Gold Fish Cracker Cutout
item.description:
This is a goldfish cracker cutter if you ever wanted to make homemade goldfish in the shape of actual goldfish.

This will allow you to cutout 15 goldfish with each stamp.

Once you have the dough rolled out to the appropriate thickness use this to cutout the dough into individual goldfish.

Here is what I found to work best:

  1. Roll out the dough to the appropriate thickness onto a pieces of parchment paper or hard surface.
  2. Press this cutter firmly into the dough until contacts the bottom surface.
  3. Make small rotations with the cookie cutter while still firmly pressing into the surface, to break each goldfish free from the cutter and even give them a more rounded shape.
  4. Place goldfish onto baking tray to bake!
    *You may need to rub some flour every so often to the cookie cutter to help avoid the crackers from sticking (depending on the dough made).

Enjoy!

item.title: Klir Di-4 Adapter Plate Red Sea Reefer 250 V3 Sump
item.description:
I spent many hours mocking this up many different ways in Tinkercad. I spent over 100 hours printing many test versions. I sold one on Ebay that really impressed the buyer who has used it for 6 months now but not much interest there so here it is for free. It is a very tight drop in fit. I use aquarium sealant to close gaps basically anywhere water touches. I ran my last model for 9 months and 3 rolls of fleece. This is my latest design.

Water does leak under the front edge of the tray into where the socks would be and makes some noise. This is why I siliconed the previous version around all edges after pushing it in place. If you can put an even bead of silicone on that edge and let it cure before installing I think it would seal pretty good.

Print time with Prusa slicer.... 20 hours. Sure it could be made thinner etc. but I wanted a solid piece of kit!
